    {"id": "api_pm_005", "question": "How would you extract a value from a response, like an auth token or a created resource's ID, and store it as a variable for a later request?", "expected_answer": "In the Tests tab: const data = pm.response.json(); pm.environment.set('token', data.token); - subsequent requests reference {{token}} in headers/URLs/body.", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "coding_problem"},
    {"id": "api_pm_006", "question": "How do you set up authentication once and reuse it across an entire Postman collection?", "expected_answer": "Configure auth at the collection level (Authorization tab) so every request inherits it by default, or capture a token in an environment variable via a login request's Tests script and reference {{token}} in each request's Authorization header/inherited auth.", "difficulty": "Advanced", "category": "scenario"},
    {"id": "api_pm_007", "question": "What is Newman, and how is it used to run Postman collections in a CI/CD pipeline?", "expected_answer": "A command-line collection runner for Postman - exports the collection/environment as JSON and runs them headlessly (newman run collection.json -e env.json), producing exit codes and reports usable in CI jobs.", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "tool"},
    {"id": "api_pm_008", "question": "How do you parameterize a Postman collection to run against multiple environments?", "expected_answer": "Define separate Environment files (dev.json, qa.json, prod.json) with the same variable names but different values, and select/pass the appropriate environment when running the collection (in the UI or via -e in Newman).", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "tool"},
    {"id": "api_pm_009", "question": "How would you use the Collection Runner (or a CSV/JSON data file) to run the same request with multiple sets of input data?", "expected_answer": "Attach a data file to the Collection Runner (or Newman's -d flag); Postman iterates the collection once per row, exposing each row's columns as data variables ({{columnName}}) inside the requests/scripts.", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "coding_problem"},
    {"id": "api_pm_010", "question": "What is a Postman Mock Server, and when would you use one?", "expected_answer": "A hosted endpoint that returns predefined example responses without a real backend - useful for testing/developing against an API contract before the actual service is implemented, or for isolating tests from a flaky dependency.", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "fundamentals"},
    {"id": "api_pm_011", "question": "How do you validate response status code, headers, and body in the Postman Tests tab?", "expected_answer": "pm.response.to.have.status(200); pm.response.to.have.header('Content-Type'); pm.expect(pm.response.json().field).to.eql(expectedValue); - Postman's chai-based assertion helpers cover all three.", "difficulty": "Basic", "category": "coding_problem"},
    {"id": "api_pm_012", "question": "What is a Postman Monitor, and how would you use it for scheduled API health checks?", "expected_answer": "A scheduled, cloud-run execution of a collection (independent of a local machine) that alerts on failures - used for ongoing production/uptime health checks rather than one-off manual or CI-triggered runs.", "difficulty": "Intermediate", "category": "fundamentals"},
    {"id": "api_pm_013", "question": "How would you design a Postman collection to test a full CRUD flow (Create -> Get -> Update -> Delete) using chained requests and variables?", "expected_answer": "Order the requests as a folder (Create, Get, Update, Delete); the Create request's Tests script saves the new resource's ID to an environment/collection variable, and each subsequent request references {{resourceId}} in its URL, keeping the whole flow dependent on real data from the previous step.", "difficulty": "Advanced", "category": "scenario"},
    {"id": "api_pm_014", "question": "How do you handle sensitive data like API keys or passwords in Postman without exposing them in a shared/exported collection?", "expected_answer": "Store secrets in environment variables marked as 'secret' type (masked in the UI and excluded from collection export by default), never hard-coded directly into request bodies/scripts that get committed or shared.", "difficulty": "Advanced", "category": "scenario"},
    {"id": "api_pm_015", "question": "What's the difference between pm.environment, pm.collectionVariables, and pm.globals in a Postman script?", "expected_answer": "pm.environment reads/writes the currently active Environment's variables; pm.collectionVariables reads/writes variables scoped to the Collection itself (available regardless of active environment); pm.globals reads/writes variables available across all collections/environments.", "difficulty": "Advanced", "category": "fundamentals"},
    {"id": "api_pm_016", "question": "How would you validate a response against a JSON Schema in Postman's Tests tab?", "expected_answer": "Use the ajv library (bundled in Postman's sandbox) or pm.response.to.have.jsonSchema(schema) to validate the parsed response body against a predefined schema object.", "difficulty": "Advanced", "category": "coding_problem"},
